# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dinosaur
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was most recently revised for its ninth edition of 1940.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] Abridged versions and a supplement exist.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was initially the basis for the 2021 *Cambridge Greek Lexicon*, although subsequently that became a complete rewrite from scratch.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The lexicon was begun in the 19th century, and is now in its ninth (revised) edition, published in 1940.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was based on the earlier *Handwörterbuch der griechischen Sprache* by the German lexicographer Franz Passow (first published in 1819, fourth edition 1831), which in turn was based on Johann Gottlob Schneider's *Kritisches griechisch-deutsches Handwörterbuch*.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Lexicon* has served as the basis for all later lexicographical work on the ancient Greek language, such as the ongoing Greek–Spanish dictionary project *Diccionario Griego–Español* (DGE).
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is now conventionally referred to as *Liddell & Scott*, *Liddell–Scott–Jones*, or *LSJ*, and its three sizes are sometimes referred to as "The Little Liddell", "The Middle Liddell" and "The Big Liddell" or "The Great Scott".
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ main edition has 116,502 entries.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] According to Stuart Jones's preface to the ninth (1925) edition, the creation of the *Lexicon* was originally proposed by David Alphonso Talboys, an Oxford publisher.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was published by the Clarendon Press at Oxford rather than by Talboys, who died before the first edition (1843) was complete.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The first editor of the LSJ, Henry George Liddell, was Dean of Christ Church, Oxford, and the father of Alice Liddell, the eponymous Alice of the writings of Lewis Carroll.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The eighth edition (1897) was the last edition published during Liddell's lifetime.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ is sometimes compared and contrasted with *A Latin Dictionary* by Lewis and Short, which was also published by Oxford University Press (OUP).
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is also sometimes compared with the Bauer lexicon, which is a similar work focused on the Greek of the New Testament.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ's definitions reflect the Victorian morality of its time, using euphemism.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, χέζω (*chezo*, 'to shit'), is translated as "ease oneself, do one's need"; βινέω (*bineo*, 'to fuck') as "inire, coire, of illicit intercourse"; and λαικάζω (*laikazo*, 'to suck cocks') as "to wench".
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] Two condensed editions of LSJ were published by Oxford University Press and remain in print.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1843, the same year as the full lexicon's publication, *A Lexicon: Abridged from Liddell and Scott's Greek–English Lexicon*, sometimes called "the Little Liddell" was published.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, a reprint, re-typeset in 2007, of the 1909 edition is available from Simon Wallenberg Press.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1889, an intermediate edition of the lexicon, *An Intermediate Greek–English Lexicon*, was prepared on the basis of the seventh edition (1883) of LSJ.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] After the publication of the ninth edition in 1940, and shortly after the deaths of both Stuart Jones and McKenzie, the OUP maintained a list of *addenda et corrigenda* ("additions and corrections"), which was bound with subsequent printings.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] However, in 1968, these were replaced by a Supplement to the LSJ.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] Neither the *addenda* nor the Supplement has ever been merged into the main text, which still stands as originally composed by Liddell, Scott, Jones, and McKenzie.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement was initially edited by M.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] Glare, editor of the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* (not to be confused with Lewis and Short's *A Latin Dictionary*).
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] Since 1988, it has been edited by Glare and Anne A.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] As the title page of the *Lexicon* makes clear (and the prefaces to the main text and to the Supplement attest), this editorial work has been performed "with the cooperation of many scholars".
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement primarily takes the form of a list of additions and corrections to the main text, sorted by entry.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The supplemental entries are marked with signs to show the nature of the changes they call for.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] Thus, a user of the *Lexicon* can consult the Supplement after consulting the main text to see whether scholarship after Jones and McKenzie has provided any new information about a particular word.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] As of 2005, the most recent revision of the Supplement, published in 1996, contains 320 pages of corrections to the main text, as well as other materials.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The small "x" indicates that this word did not appear in the main text at all; "S.*fr*." refers to the collected fragmentary works of Sophocles.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] One interesting new source of lexicographic material in the revised Supplement is the Mycenean inscriptions.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The ninth edition of LSJ has been freely available in electronic form since 2007, having been digitized by the Perseus Project.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] Diogenes, a free software package, incorporates the Perseus data and allows easy offline consultation of LSJ on Mac OS X, Windows, and Linux platforms.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] Marcion is another open source application that includes the Perseus LSJ.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] For mobile devices, both the Kindle E-Ink and the iPhone/iPod Touch feature data ported from Perseus.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Android market also currently offers the intermediate LSJ as an offline downloadable app for free or for a small price.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] A CD-ROM version published and sold by Logos Bible Software also incorporates the Supplement's additions to the ninth edition of LSJ.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] A new online version of LSJ was released in 2011 by the Thesaurus Linguae Graecae (TLG).
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The TLG version corrects "a large number of typographical errors", and includes links to the extensive TLG textual corpus.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] A Kindle version, the "Complete Liddell & Scott's Lexicon with Inflections", is also available: it allows searches of most Classical Greek word-forms and supports a growing number of Ancient/Classical Greek texts for the device.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Lexicon has been translated into Modern Greek by Xenophon Moschos, ed.: Michael Konstantinidis and was published by Anestis Konstantinidis in 1904 with the title *H.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] Scott – Α.* Κωνσταντινίδου (Μέγα Λεξικόν τῆς Ἑλληνικῆς Γλώσσης).
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] Also, a supplement compiled by a group of Greek philologists.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] An Italian translation of the *Intermediate Liddell-Scott*, entitled *Dizionario illustrato Greco-Italiano* was published in 1975 by Le Monnier, edited by Q.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] LSJ was the basis of the project of John Chadwick and James Diggle at Cambridge to publish the *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* of 2021.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] Although it was initially conceived as a mere update of LSJ, the editors eventually decided to start afresh since they considered LSJ "too antiquated in concept, design and content".
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The CGL has a smaller scope than the LSJ (and also the *Brill Dictionary of Ancient Greek*), and is unlikely to replace it; however, it is still more comprehensive than the Middle Liddell, which it intends to replace.
[src:dinosaur/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* uses contemporary language for its definitions and, unlike the LSJ, no longer elides the meaning of words considered offensive in Victorian times.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Like most theropods, abelisaurids were carnivorous bipeds.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] They were characterized by stocky hind limbs and extensive ornamentation of the skull bones, with grooves and pits.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] In many abelisaurids, such as *Carnotaurus*, the forelimbs are vestigial, the skull is shorter, and bony crests grow above the eyes.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Most of the known abelisaurids would have been between 5 and 9 m (17 to 30 ft) in length, from snout to tip of tail, with a new and as yet unnamed specimen from northwestern Turkana in Kenya, Africa reaching a possible length of 11–12 m (36 to 39 ft).
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Before becoming well known, fragmentary abelisaurid remains were occasionally misidentified as possible South American tyrannosaurids.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Abelisaurid hind limbs were more typical of ceratosaurs, with the astragalus and calcaneum (upper ankle bones) fused to each other and to the tibia, forming a tibiotarsus.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The tibia was shorter than the femur, giving the hind limb stocky proportions.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Three functional digits were on the foot (the second, third, and fourth), while the first digit, or hallux, did not contact the ground.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Although skull proportions varied, abelisaurid skulls were generally very tall and very short in length.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] In *Carnotaurus*, for example, the skull was nearly as tall as it was long.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The premaxilla in abelisaurids was very tall, so the front of the snout was blunt, not tapered as seen in many other theropods.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Two skull bones, the lacrimal and postorbital bones, projected into the eye socket from the front and back, nearly dividing it into two compartments.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The eye would have been located in the upper compartment, which was tilted slightly outwards in *Carnotaurus*, perhaps providing some degree of binocular vision.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The lacrimal and postorbital also met above the eye socket, to form a ridge or brow above the eye.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Sculpturing is seen on many of the skull bones, in the form of long grooves, pits, and protrusions.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Like other ceratosaurs, the frontal bones of the skull roof were fused together.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Carnotaurines commonly had bony projections from the skull.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] *Carnotaurus* had two pronounced horns, projecting outward above the eyes, while its close relative *Aucasaurus* had smaller projections in the same area.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] *Majungasaurus* and *Rajasaurus* had a single bony horn or dome, projecting upwards from the skull.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] These projections, like the horns of many modern animals, might have been displayed for species recognition or intimidation.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] In *Arcovenator*, the dorsal margin of the postorbital (and probably also the lacrimal) is thickened dorsolaterally, forming a strong and rugose bony brow ridge rising above the level of the skull roof.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Possibly, this rugose brow ridge supported a keratinous or scaly structure for displays.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Data for the abelisaurid fore limbs are known from *Eoabelisaurus* and the carnotaurines *Aucasaurus*, *Carnotaurus*, and *Majungasaurus*.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] All had small fore limbs, which seem to have been vestigial.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The bones of the forearm (radius and ulna) were extremely short, only 25% of the length of the upper arm (humerus) in *Carnotaurus* and 33% in *Aucasaurus*.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The entire arm was held straight, and the elbow joint was immobile.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] As is typical for ceratosaurs, the abelisaurid hand had four basic digits, but any similarity ends there.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] No wrist bones existed, with the four palm bones (metacarpals) attaching directly to the forearm.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] No phalanges (finger bones) were on the first or fourth digits, only one on the second digit and two on the third digit.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] These two external fingers were extremely short and immobile.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Manual claws were very small in *Eoabelisaurus*, and totally absent in carnotaurines.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] More primitive relatives such as *Noasaurus* and *Ceratosaurus* had longer, mobile arms with fingers and claws.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Vargas suggested a major reason for the evolution towards vestigial fore limbs in the group was because of a genetic defect; the loss of function in*HOXA11* and *HOXD11*, two genes that regulate the fore limbs' development.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Abelisaurids are typically regarded as a Cretaceous period group.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The earliest possible abelisaurid taxon is *Eoabelisaurus mefi* from the Jurassic period of Argentina, though other researchers either consider it as a ceratosaurid, an abelisauroid or its sister taxon outside abelisaurids.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Indeterminate remains are also known from the Jurassic period of Madagascar and Tanzania.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Abelisaurid remains are mainly known in the southern continents, which once made up the supercontinent of Gondwana.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] When first described in 1985, only *Carnotaurus* and *Abelisaurus* were known, both from the Late Cretaceous of South America.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Abelisaurids were then located in Late Cretaceous India (*Indosuchus* and *Rajasaurus*) and Madagascar (*Majungasaurus*), which were closely connected for much of the Cretaceous.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] It was thought that the absence of abelisaurids from continental Africa indicated that the group evolved after the separation of Africa from Gondwana, around 100 million years ago.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] However, the discovery of *Rugops* and other abelisaurid material from the middle of the Cretaceous in northern Africa disproved this hypothesis.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Mid-Cretaceous abelisaurids are now known from South America as well, showing that the group existed prior to the breakup of Gondwana.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] In 2014, the description of *Arcovenator escotae* from southern France provided the first indisputable evidence of the presence of Abelisaurids in Europe.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] *Arcovenator* presents strong similarities with the Madagascan *Majungasaurus* and Indian abelisaurids, but not with the South American forms.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] *Arcovenator*, *Majungasaurus*, and Indian forms are united in the new clade Majungasaurinae.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Paleontologists Jose Bonaparte and Fernando Novas coined the name Abelisauridae in 1985 when they described the eponymous *Abelisaurus*.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The name is formed from the family name of Roberto Abel, who discovered *Abelisaurus*, and from the Greek word σαυρος (**sauros**) meaning lizard.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The very common suffix *-idae* is usually applied to zoological family names and is derived from the Greek suffix -ιδαι (*-*idai**) meaning 'descendants'.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Abelisauridae is a family in rank-based Linnaean taxonomy, within the infraorder **Ceratosauria** and the superfamily **Abelisauroidea**, which also contains the family **Noasauridae**.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] It has had several definitions in phylogenetic taxonomy.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] It was originally defined as a node-based taxon including *Abelisaurus*, *Carnotaurus*, their common ancestor, and all of its descendants.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Later, it was redefined as a stem-based taxon, including all animals more closely related to *Abelisaurus* (or the more complete *Carnotaurus*) than to *Noasaurus*.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The node-based definition would not include animals such as *Rugops* or *Ilokelesia*, which are thought to be more basal than *Abelisaurus* and would be included by a stem-based definition.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Within the Abelisauridae is the subgroup **Carnotaurinae**, and among carnotaurines, *Aucasaurus* and *Carnotaurus* are united in **Carnotaurini**.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Complete skeletons have been described only for the most advanced abelisaurids (such as *Carnotaurus* and *Aucasaurus*), making establishment of defining features of the skeleton for the family as a whole more difficult.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] However, most are known from at least some skull bones, so known shared features come mainly from the skull.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Many abelisaurid skull features are shared with carcharodontosaurids.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] These shared features, along with the fact that abelisaurids seem to have replaced carcharodontosaurids in South America, have led to suggestions that the two groups were related.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] However, no cladistic analysis has ever found such a relationship, and aside from the skull, abelisaurids and carcharodontosaurids are very different, more similar to ceratosaurs and allosauroids, respectively.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Below is a cladogram generated by Tortosa *et al.* (2014) in the description of *Arcovenator* and creation of a new subfamily Majungasaurinae.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Some scientists include *Xenotarsosaurus* from Argentina and *Compsosuchus* from India as basal abelisaurids, while others consider them to be outside the Abelisauroidea.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The French *Genusaurus* and *Tarascosaurus* have also been called abelisaurids but both are fragmentary and may be more basal ceratosaurians, though Tortosa *et al.* (2014) considered both to be distinct abelisaurids.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Subsequent phylogenetic analyses recover *Xenotarsosaurus* and *Tarascosaurus* as an abelisaurid, but *Genusaurus* as either a noasaurid or an abelisaurid.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] With the description of *Skorpiovenator* in 2008, Canale *et al.* published another phylogenetic analysis focusing on the South American abelisaurids.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] In their results, they found that all South American forms, including *Ilokelesia* (except *Abelisaurus*), grouped together as a subclade of carnotaurines, which they named the Brachyrostra.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Sampson published new large phylogenetic analysis of ceratosaurian.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] With the description of *Eoabelisaurus*, Diego Pol and Oliver W.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Rauhut (2012) combined these analyses and added 10n new characters.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The following cladogram follows their analysis.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] In the 2021 description of *Llukalkan*, the following consensus tree was recovered.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Dental microwear features of abelisaurid teeth from the Marília Formation of Brazil indicate that they predated heavily on large prey.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Fossil teeth found amid the bones of a titanosaur from the Allen Formation of Argentina suggest that abelisaurids preyed upon or at least scavenged titanosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] Studies of the abelisaurid *Majungasaurus* indicate that it was a much slower-growing dinosaur than other theropods, taking nearly 20 years to reach adult size.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] However, other mature abelisaurid specimens indicate that they generally reached a faster rate of maturation.
[src:dinosaur/abelisaur] The holotype of *Aucasaurus* had a minimum age of 11 years, the holotype of *Niebla* had a minimum age of 9 years, and MMCh-PV 69 had a minimum age of 14 years.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] The enterprise is a subsidiary of the French publisher Média-Participations.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] Run by president and CEO Mary McAveney, Abrams publishes and distributes approximately 250 titles annually and has more than 3,000 titles in print.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] Abrams also distributes publications for the Victoria and Albert Museum, Tate, Vendome Press (in North America), Booth Clibborn Editions, SelfMadeHero, MoMA Children's Books, and 5 Continents.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] Abrams in 1949, Abrams was the first company in the United States to specialize in the creation and distribution of art books.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] Times Mirror Company acquired the company in 1966 and Harry Abrams retired in 1977.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] For many years, the company was under the direction of Paul Gottlieb (publisher) until January 2001, eighteen months before his death.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] Abrams was acquired by La Martinière Groupe in 1997.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] La Martinière was acquired by Média-Participations in 2018.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] In 2018, Abrams acquired The Overlook Press.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] In 2020, Abrams acquired Cameron + Company.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] Abrams acquired Taunton Press from Active Interest Media in May 2024.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] Founded in 2012, **Abrams Appleseed** publishes board books, novelty books, and picture books for children up to age 5.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] The imprint's list of titles includes *Alphablocks*, *Hippopposites*, *Pantone: Color*, *In My Heart*, and the *Mini Myths* series.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] Stewart, Tabori & Chang (ST&C), a publisher of cookbooks and craft titles, was purchased by Abrams in the late 1990s.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] In what CEO Michael Jacobs described in 2016 as a "unification strategy", all reprinted ST&C titles will appear under Abrams' other existing imprints.
[src:dinosaur/abrams-books] In addition, a new corporate logo was rolled out simultaneously.
[src:dinosaur/academic-press] Academic Press publishes books and reference materials in fields including communications engineering, economics, environmental science, finance, food science, geophysics, life sciences, mathematics, neuroscience, psychology, and the physical sciences.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] The **Accipitriformes** (/ækˌsɪpɪtrɪˈfɔːrmiːz/; from Latin **accipiter** 'hawk' and **formes** 'having the form of') are an order of birds that includes most of the diurnal birds of prey, including hawks, eagles, vultures, kites, ospreys and secretary birds, but not falcons or seriemas.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] The generally nocturnal owls, also considered birds of prey, are a separate order from the accipitriformes.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] For a long time, the majority view was to include them with the falcons in the Falconiformes, but many authorities now recognize a separate order Accipitriformes.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] A DNA study published in 2008 indicated that falcons are not closely related to the Accipitriformes, being instead more closely related to parrots and passerines.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] The British Ornithologists' Union already recognized the Accipitriformes, and has adopted the move of Falconiformes.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] The DNA-based proposal and the NACC and IOC classifications include the New World vultures in the Accipitriformes, while the SACC classifies the New World vultures as a separate order, the Cathartiformes.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] When Cathartiformes is considered a separate order, sister to Accipitriformes, Accipitriformes sensu lato is called Accipitrimorphae.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] The Accipitriformes are known from the Middle Eocene and typically have a sharply hooked beak with a soft cere housing the nostrils.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] Their wings are long and fairly broad, suitable for soaring flight, with the outer four to six primary feathers emarginated.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] They have strong legs and feet with raptorial claws and opposable hind claws.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] Almost all Accipitriformes are carnivorous, hunting by sight during the day or at twilight.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] They are exceptionally long-lived, and most have low reproductive rates.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] The young have a long, very fast-growing fledgling stage, followed by 3–8 weeks of nest care after first flight, and 1 to 3 years as sexually immature adults.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] The sexes have conspicuously different sizes and sometimes a female is more than twice as heavy as her mate.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] This sexual dimorphism is sometimes most extreme in specialized bird-eaters, such as the *Accipiter* hawks.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] Monogamy is the general rule, although an alternative mate is often selected if one dies.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] Accipitriformes, currently with 262 species and 75 genera in 4 extant families and possibly 1 extinct family, is the largest diurnal raptor order.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] DNA sequence analyses suggest that divergences within Accipitriformes began around the Eocene/Oligocene boundary about 34 mya, with the split of the group including genera *Elanus* and *Gampsonyx* from the other Accipitriformes genera.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] For a complete list of species, see list of Accipitriformes species.
[src:dinosaur/accipitriformes] Phylogeny of Accipitriformes sensu stricto based on Nagy, J. & Tökölyi, J.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The **acetabulum** (/ˌæsɪˈtæbjələm/; pl.: **acetabula**), also called the **cotyloid cavity**, is a concave surface of the pelvis.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The head of the femur meets with the pelvis at the acetabulum, forming the hip joint.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] There are three bones of the *os coxae* (hip bone) that come together to form the *acetabulum*.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] Contributing a little more than two-fifths of the structure is the ischium, which provides lower and side boundaries to the acetabulum.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The ilium forms the upper boundary, providing a little less than two-fifths of the structure of the acetabulum.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The rest is formed by the pubis, near the midline.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] It is bounded by a prominent uneven rim, thick and strong on top, which serves as the point of attachment for the acetabular labrum.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The acetabular labrum reduces the size of the opening of the acetabulum and deepens the surface of the hip joint.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] At the lower part of the acetabulum is the acetabular notch, which is continuous with a circular depression, the acetabular fossa, at the bottom of the cavity of the acetabulum.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The rest of the acetabulum is formed by a curved, crescent-moon shaped surface, the lunate surface, where the joint is made with the head of the femur.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] Its counterpart in the pectoral girdle is the glenoid fossa.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The acetabulum is also home to the acetabular fossa, an attachment site for the *ligamentum teres*, a triangular, somewhat flattened band implanted by its apex into the antero-superior part of the fovea capitis femoris.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The notch is converted into a foramen by the transverse acetabular ligament; through the foramen nutrient vessels and nerves enter the joint.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] This is what holds the head of the femur securely in the acetabulum.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The well-fitting surfaces of the femoral head and acetabulum, which face each other, are lined with a layer of slippery tissue called articular cartilage, which is lubricated by a thin film of synovial fluid.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] Friction inside a normal hip is less than one-tenth that of ice gliding on ice.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The acetabular branch of the obturator artery supplies the *acetabulum* through the acetabular notch.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The pubic branches supply the pelvic surface of the *acetabulum*.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] Deep branches of the superior gluteal artery supply the superior region and the inferior gluteal artery supplies the postero-inferior region.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] In reptiles and birds, the *acetabula* are deep sockets.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] Organisms in the dinosauria clade are defined by a perforate *acetabulum*, which can be thought of as a "hip-socket".
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The perforate *acetabulum* is a cup-shaped opening on each side of the pelvic girdle formed where the ischium, ilium, and pubis all meet, and into which the head of the femur inserts.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The orientation and position of the *acetabulum* is one of the main morphological traits that caused dinosaurs to walk in an upright posture with their legs directly underneath their bodies.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] In a relatively small number of dinosaurs, particularly ankylosaurians (e.g.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] *Texasetes pleurohalio*), an imperforate *acetabulum* is present, which is not an opening, but instead resembles a shallow concave depression on each side of the pelvic girdle.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] In infants and children, a Y-shaped epiphyseal plate called the triradiate cartilage joins the ilium, ischium, and pubis.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] This cartilage ossifies as the child grows.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The word *acetabulum* literally means "little vinegar cup".
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] It was the Latin word for a small vessel for serving vinegar.
[src:dinosaur/acetabulum] The word was later also used as a unit of volume.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaurs are varied from taxonomic, morphological and ecological standpoints.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Birds, at over 11,000 living species, are among the most diverse groups of vertebrates.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Using fossil evidence, paleontologists have identified over 900 distinct genera and more than 1,000 different species of non-avian dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaurs are represented on every continent by both extant species (birds) and fossil remains.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Through most of the 20th century, before birds were recognized as dinosaurs, most of the scientific community believed dinosaurs to have been sluggish and cold-blooded.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Most research conducted since the 1970s, however, has indicated that dinosaurs were active animals with elevated metabolisms and numerous adaptations for social interaction.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Evidence shows that all dinosaurs had erect legs similar to that of birds and many mammals, as opposed to the sprawling leg stance of cold-blooded tetrapods.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Some were herbivorous, others carnivorous.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Evidence suggests that all dinosaurs were egg-laying, and that nest-building was a trait shared by many dinosaurs, both avian and non-avian.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] While dinosaurs were ancestrally bipedal, many extinct groups included quadrupedal species, and some were able to shift between these stances.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Elaborate display structures such as horns or crests are common to all dinosaur groups, and some extinct groups developed skeletal modifications such as bony armor and spines.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The first dinosaur fossils were recognized in the early 19th century, with the name "dinosaur" (meaning "terrible lizard") being coined by Sir Richard Owen in 1842 to refer to these "great fossil lizards".
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Since then, mounted fossil dinosaur skeletons have been major attractions at museums worldwide, and dinosaurs have become an enduring part of popular culture.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The large sizes of some dinosaurs, as well as their seemingly monstrous and fantastic nature, have ensured their regular appearance in best-selling books and films, such as the *Jurassic Park* franchise.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Persistent public enthusiasm for the animals has resulted in significant funding for dinosaur science, and new discoveries are regularly covered by the media.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Under phylogenetic nomenclature, dinosaurs are usually defined as the group consisting of the most recent common ancestor (MRCA) of *Triceratops* and modern birds (Neornithes), and all its descendants.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] It has also been suggested that Dinosauria be defined with respect to the MRCA of *Megalosaurus* and *Iguanodon*, because these were two of the three genera cited by Richard Owen when he recognized the Dinosauria.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Both definitions cover the same known genera: Dinosauria = Ornithischia + Saurischia.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] In traditional taxonomy, birds were considered a separate class that had evolved from dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] However, most contemporary paleontologists reject the traditional style of classification based on anatomical similarity, in favor of phylogenetic taxonomy based on deduced ancestry, in which each group is defined as all descendants of a given founding genus.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Birds belong to the dinosaur subgroup Maniraptora, which are coelurosaurs, which are theropods, which are saurischians.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Barrett in 2017 suggested a radical revision of dinosaurian systematics.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Phylogenetic analysis by Baron et al. recovered the Ornithischia as being closer to the Theropoda than the Sauropodomorpha, as opposed to the traditional union of theropods with sauropodomorphs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] This would cause sauropods and kin to fall outside traditional dinosaurs, so they re-defined Dinosauria as the last common ancestor of *Triceratops horridus*, *Passer domesticus* and *Diplodocus carnegii*, and all of its descendants, to ensure that sauropods and kin remain included as dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] They also resurrected the clade Ornithoscelida to refer to the group containing Ornithischia and Theropoda.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Using one of the above definitions, dinosaurs can be generally described as archosaurs with hind limbs held erect beneath the body.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Other prehistoric animals, including pterosaurs, mosasaurs, ichthyosaurs, plesiosaurs, and *Dimetrodon*, while often popularly conceived of as dinosaurs, are not taxonomically classified as dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Pterosaurs are distantly related to dinosaurs, being members of the clade Ornithodira.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The other groups mentioned are, like dinosaurs and pterosaurs, members of Sauropsida (the reptile and bird clade), except *Dimetrodon* (which is a synapsid).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] None of them had the erect hind limb posture characteristic of true dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaurs were the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic Era, especially the Jurassic and Cretaceous periods.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Other groups of animals were restricted in size and niches; mammals, for example, rarely exceeded the size of a domestic cat and were generally rodent-sized carnivores of small prey.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaurs have always been recognized as an extremely varied group: over 900 non-avian dinosaur genera have been confidently identified (2018) with 1124 species (2016).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Estimates put the total number of dinosaur genera preserved in the fossil record at 1850, nearly 75% still undiscovered, and the number that ever existed (in or out of the fossil record) at 3,400.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] A 2016 estimate put the number of dinosaur species living in the Mesozoic at 1,543–2,468, compared to the number of modern-day birds (avian dinosaurs) at 10,806 species.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Extinct dinosaurs, as well as modern birds, include genera that are herbivorous and others carnivorous, including seed-eaters, fish-eaters, insectivores, and omnivores.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] While dinosaurs were ancestrally bipedal (as are all modern birds), some evolved into quadrupeds, and others, such as *Anchisaurus* and *Iguanodon*, could walk as easily on two or four legs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Cranial modifications like horns and crests are common dinosaurian traits, and some extinct species had bony armor.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Although the best-known genera are remarkable for their large size, many Mesozoic dinosaurs were human-sized or smaller, and modern birds are generally small in size.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaurs today inhabit every continent, and fossils show that they had achieved global distribution by the Early Jurassic epoch at latest.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Modern birds inhabit most available habitats, from terrestrial to marine, and there is evidence that some non-avian dinosaurs (such as *Microraptor*) could fly or at least glide, and others, such as spinosaurids, had semiaquatic habits.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Although some later groups of dinosaurs featured further modified versions of these traits, they are considered typical for Dinosauria; the earliest dinosaurs had them and passed them on to their descendants.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Such modifications, originating in the most recent common ancestor of a certain taxonomic group, are called the synapomorphies of such a group.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Nesbitt found a number of further potential synapomorphies and discounted a number of synapomorphies previously suggested.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] A variety of other skeletal features are shared by dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] However, because they either are common to other groups of archosaurs or were not present in all early dinosaurs, these features are not synapomorphies.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] For example, as diapsids, dinosaurs ancestrally had two pairs of Infratemporal fenestrae (openings in the skull behind the eyes), and as members of the diapsid group Archosauria, had additional openings in the snout and lower jaw.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Additionally, several characteristics once thought to be synapomorphies are now known to have appeared before dinosaurs, or were absent in the earliest dinosaurs and independently evolved by different dinosaur groups.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Another difficulty of determining distinctly dinosaurian features is that early dinosaurs and other archosaurs from the Late Triassic epoch are often poorly known and were similar in many ways; these animals have sometimes been misidentified in the literature.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaurs stand with their hind limbs erect in a manner similar to most modern mammals, but distinct from most other reptiles, whose limbs sprawl out to either side.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] This posture is due to the development of a laterally facing recess in the pelvis (usually an open socket) and a corresponding inwardly facing distinct head on the femur.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Their erect posture enabled early dinosaurs to breathe easily while moving, which likely permitted stamina and activity levels that surpassed those of "sprawling" reptiles.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Erect limbs probably also helped support the evolution of large size by reducing bending stresses on limbs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Some non-dinosaurian archosaurs, including rauisuchians, also had erect limbs but achieved this by a "pillar-erect" configuration of the hip joint, where instead of having a projection from the femur insert on a socket on the hip, the upper pelvic bone was rotated to form an overhanging shelf.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaur fossils have been known for millennia, although their true nature was not recognized.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Chinese authors have long recognised remains of prehistoric animals as "dragon bones".
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] *Huayang Guo Zhi* (華陽國志), a gazetteer compiled by Chang Qu (常璩) during the Western Jin Dynasty (265–316), reported the discovery of dragon bones at Wucheng in Sichuan Province.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] These "dragon bones" were and still are often used as ingredients for remedies in Traditional Chinese Medicine.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] While these "dragon bones" have often popularly been claimed to be dinosaur bones, all known historical examples of vertebrate "dragon bones" from China are actually from Cenozoic mammals.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] However, a village in Henan, central China was reported in 2007 to have spent the previous several decades excavating and using real dinosaur bones as "dragon bones" for TCM purposes.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] In Europe, dinosaur fossils were generally believed to be the remains of giants and other biblical creatures.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Scholarly descriptions of what would now be recognized as dinosaur bones first appeared in the late 17th century in England.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Part of a bone, now known to have been the femur of a *Megalosaurus*, was recovered from a limestone quarry at Cornwell near Chipping Norton, Oxfordshire, in 1676.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The fragment was sent to Robert Plot, Professor of Chemistry at the University of Oxford and first curator of the Ashmolean Museum, who published a description in his *The Natural History of Oxford-shire* (1677).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] He correctly identified the bone as the lower extremity of the femur of a large animal, and recognized that it was too large to belong to any known species.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] He therefore concluded it to be the femur of a huge human, perhaps a Titan or another type of giant featured in legends.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Edward Lhuyd, a friend of Sir Isaac Newton, published *Lithophylacii Britannici ichnographia* (1699), the first scientific treatment of what would now be recognized as a dinosaur.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] In it he described and named a sauropod tooth, "Rutellum impicatum", that had been found in Caswell, near Witney, Oxfordshire.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Between 1815 and 1824, the Rev William Buckland, the first Reader of Geology at the University of Oxford, collected more fossilized bones of *Megalosaurus* and became the first person to describe a non-avian dinosaur in a scientific journal.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The second non-avian dinosaur genus to be identified, *Iguanodon*, was purportedly discovered in 1822 by Mary Ann Mantell, the wife of English geologist Gideon Mantell, though this is disputed and some historians say Gideon had acquired remains years earlier.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Gideon Mantell recognized similarities between his fossils and the bones of modern iguanas and published his findings in 1825.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The term is derived from Ancient Greek δεινός*(deinos)* 'terrible, potent or fearfully great' and σαῦρος*(sauros)* 'lizard or reptile'.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Though the taxonomic name has often been interpreted as a reference to dinosaurs' teeth, claws, and other fearsome characteristics, Owen intended it also to evoke their size and majesty.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Owen recognized that the remains that had been found so far, *Iguanodon*, *Megalosaurus* and *Hylaeosaurus*, shared distinctive features, and so decided to present them as a distinct taxonomic group.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] He introduced the Dinosauria only in the revised text version of his talk published in April 1842.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] With the backing of Prince Albert, the husband of Queen Victoria, Owen established the Natural History Museum, London, to display the national collection of dinosaur fossils and other biological and geological exhibits.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] In 1858, William Parker Foulke discovered the first known American dinosaur in marl pits in the small town of Haddonfield, New Jersey.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] (Although fossils had been found before, their nature had not been correctly discerned.) The creature was named *Hadrosaurus foulkii*.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] It was an extremely important find: *Hadrosaurus* was one of the first nearly complete dinosaur skeletons found (the first was in 1834, in Maidstone, England), and it was clearly a bipedal creature.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] This was a revolutionary discovery as, until that point, most scientists had believed dinosaurs walked on four feet, like other lizards.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Foulke's discoveries sparked a wave of interests in dinosaurs in the United States, known as Dinosaur Mania.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaur mania was exemplified by the fierce rivalry between Edward Drinker Cope and Othniel Charles Marsh, both of whom raced to be the first to find new dinosaurs in what came to be known as the Bone Wars.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] This fight between the two scientists lasted for over 30 years, ending in 1897 when Cope died after spending his entire fortune on the dinosaur hunt.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Many valuable dinosaur specimens were damaged or destroyed due to the pair's rough methods: for example, their diggers often used dynamite to unearth bones.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Modern paleontologists would find such methods crude and unacceptable, since blasting easily destroys fossil and stratigraphic evidence.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Despite their unrefined methods, the contributions of Cope and Marsh to paleontology were vast: Marsh unearthed 86 new species of dinosaur and Cope discovered 56, a total of 142 new species.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Cope's collection is now at the American Museum of Natural History in New York City, while Marsh's is at the Peabody Museum of Natural History at Yale University.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] World War II caused a pause in palaeontological research; after the war, research attention was also diverted increasingly to fossil mammals rather than dinosaurs, which were seen as sluggish and cold-blooded.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] At the end of the 1960s, however, the field of dinosaur research experienced a surge in activity that remains ongoing.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Several seminal studies led to this activity.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] First, John Ostrom discovered the bird-like dromaeosaurid theropod *Deinonychus* and described it in 1969.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Its anatomy indicated that it was an active predator that was likely warm-blooded, in marked contrast to the then-prevailing image of dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Bakker published a series of studies that likewise argued for active lifestyles in dinosaurs based on anatomical and ecological evidence (see § Physiology), which were subsequently summarized in his 1986 book *The Dinosaur Heresies*.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] New revelations were supported by an increase in dinosaur discoveries.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Major new dinosaur discoveries have been made by paleontologists working in previously unexplored regions, including India, South America, Madagascar, Antarctica, and most significantly China.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Across theropods, sauropodomorphs, and ornithischians, the number of named genera began to increase drastically in the 1990s, with up to 30 new species of dinosaurs named each year by 2008.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] At least sauropodomorphs experienced a further increase in the number of named species in the 2010s, with an average of 9.3 new species having been named each year between 2009 and 2020.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] As a consequence, more sauropodomorphs were named between 1990 and 2020 than in all previous years combined.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] These new localities also led to improvements in overall specimen quality, with new species being increasingly named not on scrappy fossils but on more complete skeletons, sometimes from multiple individuals.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Better specimens also led to new species being invalidated less frequently.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Asian localities have produced the most complete theropod specimens, while North American localities have produced the most complete sauropodomorph specimens.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Prior to the dinosaur renaissance, dinosaurs were mostly classified using the traditional rank-based system of Linnaean taxonomy.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The renaissance was also accompanied by the increasingly widespread application of cladistics, a more objective method of classification based on ancestry and shared traits, which has proved tremendously useful in the study of dinosaur systematics and evolution.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Cladistic analysis, among other techniques, helps to compensate for an often incomplete and fragmentary fossil record.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Reference books summarizing the state of dinosaur research, such as David B.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Weishampel and colleagues' *The Dinosauria*, made knowledge more accessible and spurred further interest in dinosaur research.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The release of the first and second editions of *The Dinosauria* in 1990 and 2004, and of a review paper by Paul Sereno in 1998, were accompanied by increases in the number of published phylogenetic trees for dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaur fossils are not limited to bones, but also include imprints or mineralized remains of skin coverings, organs, and other tissues.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Of these, skin coverings based on keratin proteins are most easily preserved because of their cross-linked, hydrophobic molecular structure.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Fossils of keratin-based skin coverings or bony skin coverings are known from most major groups of dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaur fossils with scaly skin impressions have been found since the 19th century.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Samuel Beckles discovered a sauropod forelimb with preserved skin in 1852 that was incorrectly attributed to a crocodile; it was correctly attributed by Marsh in 1888 and subject to further study by Reginald Hooley in 1917.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Among ornithischians, in 1884 Jacob Wortman found skin impressions on the first known specimen of *Edmontosaurus annectens*, which were largely destroyed during the specimen's excavation.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Owen and Hooley subsequently described skin impressions of *Hypsilophodon* and *Iguanodon* in 1885 and 1917.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Since then, scale impressions have been most frequently found among hadrosaurids, where the impressions are known from nearly the entire body across multiple specimens.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Starting from the 1990s, major discoveries of exceptionally preserved fossils in deposits known as conservation Lagerstätten contributed to research on dinosaur soft tissues.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] In living reptiles and mammals, pigment-storing cellular structures known as melanosomes are partially responsible for producing colouration.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Both chemical traces of melanin and characteristically shaped melanosomes have been reported from feathers and scales of Jehol and Yanliao dinosaurs, including both theropods and ornithischians.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] This has enabled multiple full-body reconstructions of dinosaur colouration, such as for *Sinosauropteryx* and *Psittacosaurus* by Jakob Vinther and colleagues, and similar techniques have also been extended to dinosaur fossils from other localities.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] (However, some researchers have also suggested that fossilized melanosomes represent bacterial remains.) Stomach contents in some Jehol and Yanliao dinosaurs closely related to birds have also provided indirect indications of diet and digestive system anatomy (e.g., crops).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] More concrete evidence of internal anatomy has been reported in *Scipionyx* from the Pietraroja Plattenkalk of Italy.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] It preserves portions of the intestines, colon, liver, muscles, and windpipe.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Concurrently, a line of work led by Mary Higby Schweitzer, Jack Horner, and colleagues reported various occurrences of preserved soft tissues and proteins within dinosaur bone fossils.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Various mineralized structures that likely represented red blood cells and collagen fibres had been found by Schweitzer and others in tyrannosaurid bones as early as 1991.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] However, in 2005, Schweitzer and colleagues reported that a femur of *Tyrannosaurus* preserved soft, flexible tissue within, including blood vessels, bone matrix, and connective tissue (bone fibers) that had retained their microscopic structure.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] This discovery suggested that original soft tissues could be preserved over geological time, with multiple mechanisms having been proposed.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Later, in 2009, Schweitzer and colleagues reported that a *Brachylophosaurus* femur preserved similar microstructures, and immunohistochemical techniques (based on antibody binding) demonstrated the presence of proteins such as collagen, elastin, and laminin.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Both specimens yielded collagen protein sequences that were viable for molecular phylogenetic analyses, which grouped them with birds as would be expected.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The extraction of fragmentary DNA has also been reported for both of these fossils, along with a specimen of *Hypacrosaurus*.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] In 2015, Sergio Bertazzo and colleagues reported the preservation of collagen fibres and red blood cells in eight Cretaceous dinosaur specimens that did not show any signs of exceptional preservation, indicating that soft tissue may be preserved more commonly than previously thought.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Suggestions that these structures represent bacterial biofilms have been rejected, but cross-contamination remains a possibility that is difficult to detect.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The oldest dinosaur fossils known from substantial remains date to the Carnian epoch of the Triassic period and have been found primarily in the Ischigualasto and Santa Maria Formations of Argentina and Brazil, and the Pebbly Arkose Formation of Zimbabwe.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] *Eoraptor*'s likely resemblance to the common ancestor of all dinosaurs suggests that the first dinosaurs would have been small, bipedal predators.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The Pebbly Arkose Formation, which is of uncertain age but was likely comparable to the other two, has produced the sauropodomorph *Mbiresaurus*, along with an unnamed herrerasaurid.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Less well-preserved remains of the sauropodomorphs *Jaklapallisaurus* and *Nambalia*, along with the early saurischian *Alwalkeria*, are known from the Upper Maleri and Lower Maleri Formations of India.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The Carnian-aged Chañares Formation of Argentina preserves primitive, dinosaur-like ornithodirans such as *Lagosuchus* and *Lagerpeton* in Argentina, making it another important site for understanding dinosaur evolution.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] These ornithodirans support the model of early dinosaurs as small, bipedal predators.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaurs may have appeared as early as the Anisian epoch of the Triassic, approximately 243 million years ago, which is the age of *Nyasasaurus* from the Manda Formation of Tanzania.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] However, its known fossils are too fragmentary to identify it as a dinosaur or only a close relative.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The referral of the Manda Formation to the Anisian is also uncertain.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Regardless, dinosaurs existed alongside non-dinosaurian ornithodirans for a period of time, with estimates ranging from 5–10 million years to 21 million years.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] When dinosaurs appeared, they were not the dominant terrestrial animals.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The terrestrial habitats were occupied by various types of archosauromorphs and therapsids, like cynodonts and rhynchosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Their main competitors were the pseudosuchians, such as aetosaurs, ornithosuchids and rauisuchians, which were more successful than the dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Most of these other animals became extinct in the Triassic, in one of two events.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] First, at about 215 million years ago, a variety of basal archosauromorphs, including the protorosaurs, became extinct.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] This was followed by the Triassic–Jurassic extinction event (about 201 million years ago), that saw the end of most of the other groups of early archosaurs, like aetosaurs, ornithosuchids, phytosaurs, and rauisuchians.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Rhynchosaurs and dicynodonts survived (at least in some areas) at least as late as early –mid Norian and late Norian or earliest Rhaetian stages, respectively, and the exact date of their extinction is uncertain.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] These losses left behind a land fauna of crocodylomorphs, dinosaurs, mammals, pterosaurians, and turtles.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The first few lines of early dinosaurs diversified through the Carnian and Norian stages of the Triassic, possibly by occupying the niches of the groups that became extinct.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Also notably, there was a heightened rate of extinction during the Carnian pluvial event.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaur evolution after the Triassic followed changes in vegetation and the location of continents.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] In the Late Triassic and Early Jurassic, the continents were connected as the single landmass Pangaea, and there was a worldwide dinosaur fauna mostly composed of coelophysoid carnivores and early sauropodomorph herbivores.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Gymnosperm plants (particularly conifers), a potential food source, radiated in the Late Triassic.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Early sauropodomorphs did not have sophisticated mechanisms for processing food in the mouth, and so must have employed other means of breaking down food farther along the digestive tract.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The general homogeneity of dinosaurian faunas continued into the Middle and Late Jurassic, where most localities had predators consisting of ceratosaurians, megalosauroids, and allosauroids, and herbivores consisting of stegosaurian ornithischians and large sauropods.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Examples of this include the Morrison Formation of North America and Tendaguru Beds of Tanzania.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaurs in China show some differences, with specialized metriacanthosaurid theropods and unusual, long-necked sauropods like *Mamenchisaurus*.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Ankylosaurians and ornithopods were also becoming more common, but primitive sauropodomorphs had become extinct.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Conifers and pteridophytes were the most common plants.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Sauropods, like earlier sauropodomorphs, were not oral processors, but ornithischians were evolving various means of dealing with food in the mouth, including potential cheek-like organs to keep food in the mouth, and jaw motions to grind food.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Another notable evolutionary event of the Jurassic was the appearance of true birds, descended from maniraptoran coelurosaurians.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] By the Early Cretaceous and the ongoing breakup of Pangaea, dinosaurs were becoming strongly differentiated by landmass.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The earliest part of this time saw the spread of ankylosaurians, iguanodontians, and brachiosaurids through Europe, North America, and northern Africa.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] These were later supplemented or replaced in Africa by large spinosaurid and carcharodontosaurid theropods, and rebbachisaurid and titanosaurian sauropods, also found in South America.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] In Asia, maniraptoran coelurosaurians like dromaeosaurids, troodontids, and oviraptorosaurians became the common theropods, and ankylosaurids and early ceratopsians like *Psittacosaurus* became important herbivores.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Meanwhile, Australia was home to a fauna of basal ankylosaurians, titanosaurian sauropods and large and small Elasmarian ornithopods.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The stegosaurians appear to have gone extinct at some point in the late Early Cretaceous or early Late Cretaceous.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] A major change in the Early Cretaceous, which would be amplified in the Late Cretaceous, was the evolution of flowering plants.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] At the same time, several groups of dinosaurian herbivores evolved more sophisticated ways to orally process food.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Ceratopsians developed a method of slicing with teeth stacked on each other in batteries, and iguanodontians refined a method of grinding with dental batteries, taken to its extreme in hadrosaurids.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Some sauropods also evolved tooth batteries, best exemplified by the rebbachisaurid *Nigersaurus*.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] There were three general dinosaur faunas in the Late Cretaceous.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] In the northern continents of North America and Asia, the major theropods were tyrannosaurids and various types of smaller maniraptoran theropods, with a predominantly ornithischian herbivore assemblage of hadrosaurids, ceratopsians, ankylosaurids, and pachycephalosaurians.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] In the southern continents that had made up the now-splitting supercontinent Gondwana, abelisaurids were the common theropods, and titanosaurian sauropods the common herbivores.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Finally, in Europe, dromaeosaurids, rhabdodontid iguanodontians, nodosaurid ankylosaurians, and titanosaurian sauropods were prevalent.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Flowering plants were greatly radiating, with the first grasses appearing by the end of the Cretaceous.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Grinding hadrosaurids and shearing ceratopsians became very diverse across North America and Asia.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Theropods were also radiating as herbivores or omnivores, with therizinosaurians and ornithomimosaurians becoming common.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] The Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, which occurred approximately 66 million years ago at the end of the Cretaceous, caused the extinction of all dinosaur groups except for the neornithine birds.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Some other diapsid groups, including crocodilians, dyrosaurs, sebecosuchians, turtles, lizards, snakes, sphenodontians, and choristoderans, also survived the event.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] It is often stated that mammals out-competed the neornithines for dominance of most terrestrial niches but many of these groups co-existed with rich mammalian faunas for most of the Cenozoic Era.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaurs belong to a group known as archosaurs, which also includes modern crocodilians.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Within the archosaur group, dinosaurs are differentiated most noticeably by their gait.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Dinosaur legs extend directly beneath the body, whereas the legs of lizards and crocodilians sprawl out to either side.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Collectively, dinosaurs as a clade are divided into two primary branches, Saurischia and Ornithischia.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Saurischia includes those taxa sharing a more recent common ancestor with birds than with Ornithischia, while Ornithischia includes all taxa sharing a more recent common ancestor with *Triceratops* than with Saurischia.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Anatomically, these two groups can be distinguished most noticeably by their pelvic structure.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Early saurischians—"lizard-hipped", from the Greek **sauros** (σαῦρος) meaning "lizard" and **ischion** (ἰσχίον) meaning "hip joint"—retained the hip structure of their ancestors, with a pubis bone directed cranially, or forward.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] This basic form was modified by rotating the pubis backward to varying degrees in several groups (*Herrerasaurus*, therizinosauroids, dromaeosaurids, and birds).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Saurischia includes the theropods (exclusively bipedal and with a wide variety of diets) and sauropodomorphs (long-necked herbivores which include advanced, quadrupedal groups).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] By contrast, ornithischians—"bird-hipped", from the Greek *ornis* (ὀρνίς) meaning "bird" and *ischion* (ἰσχίον) meaning "hip joint"—had a pelvis that superficially resembled a bird's pelvis: the pubic bone was oriented caudally (rear-pointing).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Unlike birds, the ornithischian pubis also usually had an additional forward-pointing process.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Ornithischia includes a variety of species that were primarily herbivores.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Despite the terms "bird hip" (Ornithischia) and "lizard hip" (Saurischia), birds are not part of Ornithischia.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p01] Birds instead belong to Saurischia, the "lizard-hipped" dinosaurs—birds evolved from earlier dinosaurs with "lizard hips".
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Knowledge about dinosaurs is derived from a variety of fossil and non-fossil records, including fossilized bones, feces, trackways, gastroliths, feathers, impressions of skin, internal organs and other soft tissues.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Many fields of study contribute to our understanding of dinosaurs, including physics (especially biomechanics), chemistry, biology, and the Earth sciences (of which paleontology is a sub-discipline).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Two topics of particular interest and study have been dinosaur size and behavior.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Current evidence suggests that dinosaur average size varied through the Triassic, Early Jurassic, Late Jurassic and Cretaceous.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The mode of Mesozoic dinosaur body masses is between 1 and 10 metric tons (1.1 and 11.0 short tons).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This contrasts sharply with the average size of Cenozoic mammals, estimated by the National Museum of Natural History as about 2 to 5 kg (4.4 to 11.0 lb).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The sauropods were the largest and heaviest dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] For much of the dinosaur era, the smallest sauropods were larger than anything else in their habitat, and the largest was an order of magnitude more massive than anything else that has since walked the Earth.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Giant prehistoric mammals such as *Paraceratherium* (the largest land mammal ever) were dwarfed by the giant sauropods, and only modern whales approach or surpass them in size.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] There are several proposed advantages for the large size of sauropods, including protection from predation, reduction of energy use, and longevity, but it may be that the most important advantage was dietary.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Large animals are more efficient at digestion than small animals, because food spends more time in their digestive systems.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This also permits them to subsist on food with lower nutritive value than smaller animals.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Sauropod remains are mostly found in rock formations interpreted as dry or seasonally dry, and the ability to eat large quantities of low-nutrient browse would have been advantageous in such environments.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Scientists will probably never be certain of the largest and smallest dinosaurs to have ever existed.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This is because only a tiny percentage of animals were ever fossilized and most of these remain buried in the earth.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Few non-avian dinosaur specimens that are recovered are complete skeletons, and impressions of skin and other soft tissues are rare.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Rebuilding a complete skeleton by comparing the size and morphology of bones to those of similar, better-known species is an inexact art, and reconstructing the muscles and other organs of the living animal is, at best, a process of educated guesswork.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The tallest and heaviest dinosaur known from good skeletons is *Giraffatitan brancai* (previously classified as a species of *Brachiosaurus*).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Its remains were discovered in Tanzania between 1907 and 1912.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The longest complete dinosaur is the 27 meters (89 ft) long *Diplodocus*, which was discovered in Wyoming in the United States and displayed in Pittsburgh's Carnegie Museum of Natural History in 1907.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The longest dinosaur known from good fossil material is *Patagotitan*: the skeleton mount in the American Museum of Natural History in New York is 37 meters (121 ft) long.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The Museo Municipal Carmen Funes in Plaza Huincul, Argentina, has an *Argentinosaurus* reconstructed skeleton mount that is 39.7 meters (130 ft) long.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] There were larger dinosaurs, but knowledge of them is based entirely on a small number of fragmentary fossils.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] There were a few dinosaurs that were considered either the heaviest or longest.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The most famous include *Amphicoelias fragillimus*, known only from a now lost partial vertebral neural arch described in 1878.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Extrapolating from the illustration of this bone, the animal may have been 58 meters (190 ft) long and weighed 122400 kg (269800 lb).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, recent research has reclassified *Amphicoelias* from the long, gracile diplodocid to the shorter but much stockier rebbachisaurid.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Now renamed as *Maraapunisaurus*, this sauropod measured as much as 40 meters (130 ft) long and weighed as much as 120000 kg (260000 lb).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Another contender of this title includes *Bruhathkayosaurus*, a controversial taxon that was recently confirmed to exist after archived photos were uncovered.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] *Bruhathkayosaurus* was a titanosaur and would have most likely weighed more than even *Maraapunisaurus*.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Recent size estimates in 2023 have this sauropod reaching lengths of up to 44 m (144 ft) long and placed in a colossal weight range of around 110000–170000 kg (240000–370000 lb).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] If these upper estimates are true, *Bruhathkayosaurus* would have rivaled the blue whale and *Perucetus colossus* as one of the largest animals to have ever existed.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The largest carnivorous dinosaur was *Spinosaurus*, reaching a length of 12.6 to 18 meters (41 to 59 ft) and weighing 7 to 20.9 metric tons (7.7 to 23.0 short tons).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Other large carnivorous theropods included *Giganotosaurus*, *Carcharodontosaurus*, and *Tyrannosaurus*.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] *Therizinosaurus* and *Deinocheirus* were among the tallest of the theropods.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The largest ornithischian dinosaur was probably the hadrosaurid *Shantungosaurus giganteus*, which measured 16.6 meters (54 ft).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The largest individuals may have weighed as much as 16 metric tons (18 short tons).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The smallest dinosaur known is the bee hummingbird, with a length of only 5 centimeters (2.0 in) and mass of around 1.8 g (0.063 oz).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The smallest known non-avialan dinosaurs were about the size of pigeons and were those theropods most closely related to birds.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] For example, *Anchiornis huxleyi* is currently the smallest non-avialan dinosaur described from an adult specimen, with an estimated weight of 110 g (3.9 oz) and a total skeletal length of 34 centimeters (1.12 ft).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The smallest herbivorous non-avialan dinosaurs included *Microceratus* and *Wannanosaurus*, at about 60 centimeters (2.0 ft) long each.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Many modern birds are highly social, often found living in flocks.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] There is general agreement that some behaviors that are common in birds, as well as in crocodilians (closest living relatives of birds), were also common among extinct dinosaur groups.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Interpretations of behavior in fossil species are generally based on the pose of skeletons and their habitat, computer simulations of their biomechanics, and comparisons with modern animals in similar ecological niches.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Other mass-death sites have been discovered subsequently.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Those, along with multiple trackways, suggest that gregarious behavior was common in many early dinosaur species.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Trackways of hundreds or even thousands of herbivores indicate that duck-billed (hadrosaurids) may have moved in great herds, like the American bison or the African springbok.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Sauropod tracks document that these animals traveled in groups composed of several different species, at least in Oxfordshire, England, although there is no evidence for specific herd structures.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Congregating into herds may have evolved for defense, for migratory purposes, or to provide protection for young.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] There is evidence that many types of slow-growing dinosaurs, including various theropods, sauropods, ankylosaurians, ornithopods, and ceratopsians, formed aggregations of immature individuals.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] One example is a site in Inner Mongolia that has yielded remains of over 20 *Sinornithomimus*, from one to seven years old.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This assemblage is interpreted as a social group that was trapped in mud.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The interpretation of dinosaurs as gregarious has also extended to depicting carnivorous theropods as pack hunters working together to bring down large prey.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The crests and frills of some dinosaurs, like the marginocephalians, theropods and lambeosaurines, may have been too fragile to be used for active defense, and so they were likely used for sexual or aggressive displays, though little is known about dinosaur mating and territorialism.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Head wounds from bites suggest that theropods, at least, engaged in active aggressive confrontations.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] From a behavioral standpoint, one of the most valuable dinosaur fossils was discovered in the Gobi Desert in 1971.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] It included a *Velociraptor* attacking a *Protoceratops*, providing evidence that dinosaurs did indeed attack each other.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Additional evidence for attacking live prey is the partially healed tail of an *Edmontosaurus*, a hadrosaurid dinosaur; the tail is damaged in such a way that shows the animal was bitten by a tyrannosaur but survived.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Cannibalism amongst some species of dinosaurs was confirmed by tooth marks found in Madagascar in 2003, involving the theropod *Majungasaurus*.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Comparisons between the scleral rings of dinosaurs and modern birds and reptiles have been used to infer daily activity patterns of dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Although it has been suggested that most dinosaurs were active during the day, these comparisons have shown that small predatory dinosaurs such as dromaeosaurids, *Juravenator*, and *Megapnosaurus* were likely nocturnal.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Large and medium-sized herbivorous and omnivorous dinosaurs such as ceratopsians, sauropodomorphs, hadrosaurids, ornithomimosaurs may have been cathemeral, active during short intervals throughout the day, although the small ornithischian *Agilisaurus* was inferred to be diurnal.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Based on fossil evidence from dinosaurs such as *Oryctodromeus*, some ornithischian species seem to have led a partially fossorial (burrowing) lifestyle.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Many modern birds are arboreal (tree climbing), and this was also true of many Mesozoic birds, especially the enantiornithines.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] While some early bird-like species may have already been arboreal as well (including dromaeosaurids) such as *Microraptor*) most non-avialan dinosaurs seem to have relied on land-based locomotion.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] A good understanding of how dinosaurs moved on the ground is key to models of dinosaur behavior; the science of biomechanics, pioneered by Robert McNeill Alexander, has provided significant insight in this area.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] For example, studies of the forces exerted by muscles and gravity on dinosaurs' skeletal structure have investigated how fast dinosaurs could run, whether diplodocids could create sonic booms via whip-like tail snapping, and whether sauropods could float.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Modern birds communicate by visual and auditory signals, and the wide diversity of visual display structures among fossil dinosaur groups, such as horns, frills, crests, sails, and feathers, suggests that visual communication has always been important in dinosaur biology.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Reconstruction of the plumage color of *Anchiornis* suggest the importance of color in visual communication in non-avian dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] A 2009 review indicated that non-avians used visual displays and possibly non-vocal sounds, such as hissing, jaw-grinding or -clapping, splashing, and wing-beating (possible in winged maniraptoran dinosaurs).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Fossilized larynxes or voice boxes have been identified in two dinosaurs; the ankylosaurid *Pinacosaurus* and the neornithischian *Pulaosaurus*, the structures of which suggest that dinosaurs were capable of complex bird-like vocalizations.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] A 2016 study concludes that some dinosaurs may have produced closed-mouth vocalizations, such as cooing, hooting, and booming.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] These occur in both reptiles and birds and involve inflating the esophagus or tracheal pouches.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Such vocalizations evolved independently in extant archosaurs numerous times, following increases in body size.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The crests of some hadrosaurids and the nasal chambers of ankylosaurids may have been resonators.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Birds have evolved a novel organ for vocalization, the syrinx, the earliest remains of which were found in a specimen of the duck-like *Vegavis iaai* dated 69 –66 million years ago.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The syrinx may have supplemented and then replaced the larynx as a vocal organ during bird evolution.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Dinosaur eggs were usually laid in a nest.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Most species create somewhat elaborate nests which can be cups, domes, plates, beds scrapes, mounds, or burrows.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Some species of modern bird have no nests; the cliff-nesting common guillemot lays its eggs on bare rock, and male emperor penguins keep eggs between their body and feet.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Primitive birds and many non-avialan dinosaurs often lay eggs in communal nests, with males primarily incubating the eggs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] While modern birds have only one functional oviduct and lay one egg at a time, more primitive birds and other dinosaurs had two oviducts, like crocodiles.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Some non-avialan dinosaurs, such as *Troodon*, exhibited iterative laying, where the adult might lay a pair of eggs every one or two days, and then ensured simultaneous hatching by delaying brooding until all eggs were laid.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] When laying eggs, females grow a special type of bone between the hard outer bone and the marrow of their limbs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This medullary bone, which is rich in calcium, is used to make eggshells.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] A discovery of features in a *Tyrannosaurus* skeleton provided evidence of medullary bone in extinct dinosaurs and, for the first time, allowed paleontologists to establish the sex of a fossil dinosaur specimen.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Further research has found medullary bone in the carnosaur *Allosaurus* and the ornithopod *Tenontosaurus*.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Because the line of dinosaurs that includes *Allosaurus* and *Tyrannosaurus* diverged from the line that led to *Tenontosaurus* very early in the evolution of dinosaurs, this suggests that the production of medullary tissue is a general characteristic of all dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Another widespread trait among modern birds (but see below in regards to fossil groups and extant megapodes) is parental care for young after hatching.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Bob Makela and Jack Horner's 1978 discovery of a *Maiasaura* ("good mother lizard") nesting ground in Montana demonstrated that parental care continued long after birth among ornithopods.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] A specimen of the oviraptorid *Citipati osmolskae* was discovered in a chicken-like brooding position in 1993, which may indicate that they had begun using an insulating layer of feathers to keep the eggs warm.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] An embryo of the basal sauropodomorph *Massospondylus* was found without teeth, indicating that some parental care was required to feed the young dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Trackways have also confirmed parental behavior among ornithopods from the Isle of Skye in northwestern Scotland.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, there is ample evidence of precociality or superprecociality among many dinosaur species, particularly theropods.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] For instance, non-ornithuromorph birds have been abundantly demonstrated to have had slow growth rates, megapode-like egg burying behavior and the ability to fly soon after birth.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Both *Tyrannosaurus* and *Troodon* had juveniles with clear superprecociality and likely occupying different ecological niches than the adults.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Superprecociality has been inferred for sauropods.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Genital structures are unlikely to fossilize as they lack scales that may allow preservation via pigmentation or residual calcium phosphate salts.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In 2021, the best preserved specimen of a dinosaur's cloacal vent exterior was described for *Psittacosaurus*, demonstrating lateral swellings similar to crocodylian musk glands used in social displays by both sexes and pigmented regions which could also reflect a signalling function.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, this specimen on its own does not offer enough information to determine whether this dinosaur had sexual signalling functions; it only supports the possibility.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Cloacal visual signalling can occur in either males or females in living birds, making it unlikely to be useful to determine sex for extinct dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Because both modern crocodilians and birds have four-chambered hearts (albeit modified in crocodilians), it is likely that this is a trait shared by all archosaurs, including all dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] While all modern birds have high metabolisms and are endothermic ("warm-blooded"), a vigorous debate has been ongoing since the 1960s regarding how far back in the dinosaur lineage this trait extended.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Various researchers have supported dinosaurs as being endothermic, ectothermic ("cold-blooded"), or somewhere in between.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] An emerging consensus among researchers is that, while different lineages of dinosaurs would have had different metabolisms, most of them had higher metabolic rates than other reptiles but lower than living birds and mammals, which is termed mesothermy by some.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Evidence from crocodiles and their extinct relatives suggests that such elevated metabolisms could have developed in the earliest archosaurs, which were the common ancestors of dinosaurs and crocodiles.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] After non-avian dinosaurs were discovered, paleontologists first posited that they were ectothermic.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This was used to imply that the ancient dinosaurs were relatively slow, sluggish organisms, even though many modern reptiles are fast and light-footed despite relying on external sources of heat to regulate their body temperature.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The idea of dinosaurs as ectothermic remained a prevalent view until Robert T.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Bakker, an early proponent of dinosaur endothermy, published an influential paper on the topic in 1968.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Bakker specifically used anatomical and ecological evidence to argue that sauropods, which had hitherto been depicted as sprawling aquatic animals with their tails dragging on the ground, were endotherms that lived vigorous, terrestrial lives.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In 1972, Bakker expanded on his arguments based on energy requirements and predator-prey ratios.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This was one of the seminal results that led to the dinosaur renaissance.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] One of the greatest contributions to the modern understanding of dinosaur physiology has been paleohistology, the study of microscopic tissue structure in dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] From the 1960s forward, Armand de Ricqlès suggested that the presence of fibrolamellar bone—bony tissue with an irregular, fibrous texture and filled with blood vessels—was indicative of consistently fast growth and therefore endothermy.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Fibrolamellar bone was common in both dinosaurs and pterosaurs, though not universally present.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This has led to a significant body of work in reconstructing growth curves and modeling the evolution of growth rates across various dinosaur lineages, which has suggested overall that dinosaurs grew faster than living reptiles.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In saurischian dinosaurs, higher metabolisms were supported by the evolution of the avian respiratory system, characterized by an extensive system of air sacs that extended the lungs and invaded many of the bones in the skeleton, making them hollow.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The rapid airflow would also have been an effective cooling mechanism, which in conjunction with a lower metabolic rate would have prevented large sauropods from overheating.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] These traits may have enabled sauropods to grow quickly to gigantic sizes.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Sauropods may also have benefitted from their size—their small surface area to volume ratio meant that they would have been able to thermoregulate more easily, a phenomenon termed gigantothermy.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Like other reptiles, dinosaurs are primarily uricotelic, that is, their kidneys extract nitrogenous wastes from their bloodstream and excrete it as uric acid instead of urea or ammonia via the ureters into the intestine.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This would have helped them to conserve water.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In most living species, uric acid is excreted along with feces as a semisolid waste.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, at least some modern birds (such as hummingbirds) can be facultatively ammonotelic, excreting most of the nitrogenous wastes as ammonia.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This material, as well as the output of the intestines, emerges from the cloaca.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In addition, many species regurgitate pellets, and fossil pellets are known as early as the Jurassic from *Anchiornis*.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The size and shape of the brain can be partly reconstructed based on the surrounding bones.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In 1896, Marsh calculated ratios between brain weight and body weight of seven species of dinosaurs, showing that the brain of dinosaurs was proportionally smaller than in today's crocodiles, and that the brain of *Stegosaurus* was smaller than in any living land vertebrate.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This contributed to the widespread public notion of dinosaurs as being sluggish and extraordinarily stupid.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Harry Jerison, in 1973, showed that proportionally smaller brains are expected at larger body sizes, and that brain size in dinosaurs was not smaller than expected when compared to living reptiles.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Later research showed that relative brain size progressively increased during the evolution of theropods, with the highest intelligence – comparable to that of modern birds – calculated for the troodontid *Troodon*.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The possibility that dinosaurs were the ancestors of birds was first suggested in 1868 by Thomas Henry Huxley.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] After the work of Gerhard Heilmann in the early 20th century, the theory of birds as dinosaur descendants was abandoned in favor of the idea of them being descendants of generalized thecodonts, with the key piece of evidence being the supposed lack of clavicles in dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, as later discoveries showed, clavicles (or a single fused wishbone, which derived from separate clavicles) were not actually absent; they had been found as early as 1924 in *Oviraptor*, but misidentified as an interclavicle.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In the 1970s, John Ostrom revived the dinosaur–bird theory, which gained momentum in the coming decades with the advent of cladistic analysis, and a great increase in the discovery of small theropods and early birds.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Of particular note have been the fossils of the Jehol Biota, where a variety of theropods and early birds have been found, often with feathers of some type.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Birds share over a hundred distinct anatomical features with other theropod dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] They are most closely allied with maniraptoran coelurosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Feathers are one of the most recognizable characteristics of modern birds, and a trait that was also shared by several non-avian dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Based on the current distribution of fossil evidence, it appears that feathers were an ancestral dinosaurian trait, though one that may have been selectively lost in some species.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Direct fossil evidence of feathers or feather-like structures has been discovered in a diverse array of species in many non-avian dinosaur groups, both among saurischians and ornithischians.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Simple, branched, feather-like structures are known from heterodontosaurids, primitive neornithischians, and theropods, and primitive ceratopsians.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Evidence for true, vaned feathers similar to the flight feathers of modern birds has been found only in the theropod subgroup Maniraptora, which includes oviraptorosaurs, troodontids, dromaeosaurids, and birds.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Feather-like structures known as pycnofibres have also been found in pterosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, researchers do not agree on whether these structures share a common origin between lineages (i.e., they are homologous), or if they were the result of widespread experimentation with skin coverings among ornithodirans.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] If the former is the case, filaments may have been common in the ornithodiran lineage and evolved before the appearance of dinosaurs themselves.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Research into the genetics of American alligators has revealed that crocodylian scutes do possess feather-keratins during embryonic development, but these keratins are not expressed by the animals before hatching.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, their views have for the most part not been accepted by other researchers, to the point that the scientific nature of Feduccia's proposals has been questioned.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Because feathers are often associated with birds, feathered dinosaurs are often touted as the missing link between birds and dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, the multiple skeletal features also shared by the two groups represent another important line of evidence for paleontologists.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Areas of the skeleton with important similarities include the neck, pubis, wrist (semi-lunate carpal), arm and pectoral girdle, furcula (wishbone), and breast bone.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Comparison of bird and dinosaur skeletons through cladistic analysis strengthens the case for the link.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Large meat-eating dinosaurs had a complex system of air sacs similar to those found in modern birds, according to a 2005 investigation led by Patrick M.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The lungs of theropod dinosaurs (carnivores that walked on two legs and had bird-like feet) likely pumped air into hollow sacs in their skeletons, as is the case in birds.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] "What was once formally considered unique to birds was present in some form in the ancestors of birds", O'Connor said.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In 2008, scientists described *Aerosteon riocoloradensis*, the skeleton of which supplies the strongest evidence to date of a dinosaur with a bird-like breathing system.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] CT scanning of *Aerosteon'*s fossil bones revealed evidence for the existence of air sacs within the animal's body cavity.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Fossils of the troodonts *Mei* and *Sinornithoides* demonstrate that some dinosaurs slept with their heads tucked under their arms.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This behavior, which may have helped to keep the head warm, is also characteristic of modern birds.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Several deinonychosaur and oviraptorosaur specimens have also been found preserved on top of their nests, likely brooding in a bird-like manner.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The ratio between egg volume and body mass of adults among these dinosaurs suggest that the eggs were primarily brooded by the male and that the young were highly precocial, similar to many modern ground-dwelling birds.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Some dinosaurs are known to have used gizzard stones like modern birds.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] These stones are swallowed by animals to aid digestion and break down food and hard fibers once they enter the stomach.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] When found in association with fossils, gizzard stones are called gastroliths.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] All non-avian dinosaurs and most lineages of birds became extinct in a mass extinction event, called the Cretaceous–Paleogene (K-Pg) extinction event, at the end of the Cretaceous period.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Above the Cretaceous–Paleogene boundary, which has been dated to 66.038 ± 0.025 million years ago, fossils of non-avian dinosaurs disappear abruptly; the absence of dinosaur fossils was historically used to assign rocks to the ensuing Cenozoic.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The nature of the event that caused this mass extinction has been extensively studied since the 1970s, leading to the development of two mechanisms that are thought to have played major roles: an extraterrestrial impact event in the Yucatán Peninsula, along with flood basalt volcanism in India.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, the specific mechanisms of the extinction event and the extent of its effects on dinosaurs are still areas of ongoing research.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Alongside dinosaurs, many other groups of animals became extinct: pterosaurs, marine reptiles such as mosasaurs and plesiosaurs, several groups of mammals, ammonites (nautilus-like mollusks), rudists (reef-building bivalves), and various groups of marine plankton.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In all, approximately 47% of genera and 76% of species on Earth became extinct during the K-Pg extinction event.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Just before the K-Pg extinction event, the number of non-avian dinosaur species that existed globally has been estimated at between 628 and 1078.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] It remains uncertain whether the diversity of dinosaurs was in gradual decline before the K-Pg extinction event, or whether dinosaurs were actually thriving prior to the extinction.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Rock formations from the Maastrichtian epoch, which directly preceded the extinction, have been found to have lower diversity than the preceding Campanian epoch, which led to the prevailing view of a long-term decline in diversity.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, these comparisons did not account either for varying preservation potential between rock units or for different extents of exploration and excavation.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In 1984, Dale Russell carried out an analysis to account for these biases, and found no evidence of a decline; another analysis by David Fastovsky and colleagues in 2004 even showed that dinosaur diversity continually increased until the extinction, but this analysis has been rebutted.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Since then, different approaches based on statistics and mathematical models have variously supported either a sudden extinction or a gradual decline.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] End-Cretaceous trends in diversity may have varied between dinosaur lineages: it has been suggested that sauropods were not in decline, while ornithischians and theropods were in decline.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The bolide impact hypothesis, first brought to wide attention in 1980 by Walter Alvarez, Luis Alvarez, and colleagues, attributes the K-Pg extinction event to a bolide (extraterrestrial projectile) impact.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Alvarez and colleagues proposed that a sudden increase in iridium levels, recorded around the world in rock deposits at the Cretaceous–Paleogene boundary, was direct evidence of the impact.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Shocked quartz, indicative of a strong shockwave emanating from an impact, was also found worldwide.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The actual impact site remained elusive until a crater measuring 180 km (110 mi) wide was discovered in the Yucatán Peninsula of southeastern Mexico, and was publicized in a 1991 paper by Alan Hildebrand and colleagues.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Now, the bulk of the evidence suggests that a bolide 5 to 15 kilometers (3 to 9+1⁄2 miles) wide impacted the Yucatán Peninsula 66 million years ago, forming this crater and creating a "kill mechanism" that triggered the extinction event.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Within hours, the Chicxulub impact would have created immediate effects such as earthquakes, tsunamis, and a global firestorm that likely killed unsheltered animals and started wildfires.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, it would also have had longer-term consequences for the environment.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Within days, sulfate aerosols released from rocks at the impact site would have contributed to acid rain and ocean acidification.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Soot aerosols are thought to have spread around the world over the ensuing months and years; they would have cooled the surface of the Earth by reflecting thermal radiation, and greatly slowed photosynthesis by blocking out sunlight, thus creating an impact winter.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] (This role was ascribed to sulfate aerosols until experiments demonstrated otherwise.) The cessation of photosynthesis would have led to the collapse of food webs depending on leafy plants, which included all dinosaurs save for grain-eating birds.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] At the time of the K-Pg extinction, the Deccan Traps flood basalts of India were actively erupting.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The eruptions can be separated into three phases around the K-Pg boundary, two prior to the boundary and one after.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The second phase, which occurred very close to the boundary, would have extruded 70 to 80% of the volume of these eruptions in intermittent pulses that occurred around 100,000 years apart.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Greenhouse gases such as carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide would have been released by this volcanic activity, resulting in climate change through temperature perturbations of roughly 3 °C (5.4 °F) but possibly as high as 7 °C (13 °F).
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Like the Chicxulub impact, the eruptions may also have released sulfate aerosols, which would have caused acid rain and global cooling.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, due to large error margins in the dating of the eruptions, the role of the Deccan Traps in the K-Pg extinction remains unclear.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Before 2000, arguments that the Deccan Traps eruptions—as opposed to the Chicxulub impact—caused the extinction were usually linked to the view that the extinction was gradual.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Prior to the discovery of the Chicxulub crater, the Deccan Traps were used to explain the global iridium layer; even after the crater's discovery, the impact was still thought to only have had a regional, not global, effect on the extinction event.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In response, Luis Alvarez rejected volcanic activity as an explanation for the iridium layer and the extinction as a whole.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Since then, however, most researchers have adopted a more moderate position, which identifies the Chicxulub impact as the primary progenitor of the extinction while also recognizing that the Deccan Traps may also have played a role.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Walter Alvarez himself has acknowledged that the Deccan Traps and other ecological factors may have contributed to the extinctions in addition to the Chicxulub impact.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Some estimates have placed the start of the second phase in the Deccan Traps eruptions within 50,000 years after the Chicxulub impact.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Combined with mathematical modelling of the seismic waves that would have been generated by the impact, this has led to the suggestion that the Chicxulub impact may have triggered these eruptions by increasing the permeability of the mantle plume underlying the Deccan Traps.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Whether the Deccan Traps were a major cause of the extinction, on par with the Chicxulub impact, remains uncertain.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Proponents consider the climatic impact of the sulfur dioxide released to have been on par with the Chicxulub impact, and also note the role of flood basalt volcanism in other mass extinctions like the Permian-Triassic extinction event.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] They consider the Chicxulub impact to have worsened the ongoing climate change caused by the eruptions.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Meanwhile, detractors point out the sudden nature of the extinction and that other pulses in Deccan Traps activity of comparable magnitude did not appear to have caused extinctions.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] They also contend that the causes of different mass extinctions should be assessed separately.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In 2020, Alfio Chiarenza and colleagues suggested that the Deccan Traps may even have had the opposite effect: they suggested that the long-term warming caused by its carbon dioxide emissions may have dampened the impact winter from the Chicxulub impact.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Non-avian dinosaur remains have occasionally been found above the K-Pg boundary.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In 2000, Spencer Lucas and colleagues reported the discovery of a single hadrosaur right femur in the San Juan Basin of New Mexico, and described it as evidence of Paleocene dinosaurs.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The rock unit in which the bone was discovered has been dated to the early Paleocene epoch, approximately 64.8 million years ago.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] If the bone was not re-deposited by weathering action, it would provide evidence that some dinosaur populations survived at least half a million years into the Cenozoic.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Other evidence includes the presence of dinosaur remains in the Hell Creek Formation up to 1.3 m (4.3 ft) above the Cretaceous–Paleogene boundary, representing 40,000 years of elapsed time.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] This has been used to support the view that the K-Pg extinction was gradual.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] However, these supposed Paleocene dinosaurs are considered by many other researchers to be reworked, that is, washed out of their original locations and then reburied in younger sediments.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The age estimates have also been considered unreliable.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] By human standards, dinosaurs were creatures of fantastic appearance and often enormous size.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] As such, they have captured the popular imagination and become an enduring part of human culture.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The entry of the word "dinosaur" into the common vernacular reflects the animals' cultural importance: in English, "dinosaur" is commonly used to describe anything that is impractically large, obsolete, or bound for extinction.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Public enthusiasm for dinosaurs first developed in Victorian England, where in 1854, three decades after the first scientific descriptions of dinosaur remains, a menagerie of lifelike dinosaur sculptures was unveiled in London's Crystal Palace Park.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The Crystal Palace dinosaurs proved so popular that a strong market in smaller replicas soon developed.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In subsequent decades, dinosaur exhibits opened at parks and museums around the world, ensuring that successive generations would be introduced to the animals in an immersive and exciting way.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The enduring popularity of dinosaurs, in its turn, has resulted in significant public funding for dinosaur science, and has frequently spurred new discoveries.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] In the United States, for example, the competition between museums for public attention led directly to the Bone Wars of the 1880s and 1890s, during which a pair of feuding paleontologists made enormous scientific contributions.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] The popular preoccupation with dinosaurs has ensured their appearance in literature, film, and other media.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Beginning in 1852 with a passing mention in Charles Dickens' *Bleak House*, dinosaurs have been featured in large numbers of fictional works.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Authors of general-interest non-fiction works about dinosaurs, including some prominent paleontologists, have often sought to use the animals as a way to educate readers about science in general.
[src:dinosaur/dinosaur-p02] Dinosaurs are ubiquitous in advertising; numerous companies have referenced dinosaurs in printed or televised advertisements, either in order to sell their own products or in order to characterize their rivals as slow-moving, dim-witted, or obsolete.
